# Software architecture

- Prefer the simplest architecture that meets current requirements; defer distributed complexity until justified.
- Define clear boundaries: API layer, domain logic, data access, infrastructure.
- Favor dependency inversion — business logic must not depend on frameworks or databases directly.
- Document key decisions (ADRs) when choosing between viable architectures.
- Design for observability from day one: structured logs, metrics, traces at service boundaries.
- Make failure modes explicit: timeouts, retries, circuit breakers, graceful degradation.
- Avoid shared mutable state across services; prefer event-driven or explicit API contracts.
- When scaling, identify the bottleneck first (CPU, I/O, DB, network) before adding layers.
- Keep deployment units small and independently deployable where possible.
- Question every new dependency — each one is a long-term maintenance cost.
